cted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor over a decade, Canada’s participation in the war in Afghanistan dominated media headlines, government discussions, academic studies, and the public international security debate, often to the exclusion of issues that have traditionally shaped Canadian approaches to security and defence policy. Now that the mission in Afghanistan is over, what issues should define Canada’s international security agenda? This collection of essays, written by leading observers of Canadian policy, seeks to answer this question by investigating how Canada will likely respond to new threats and security challenges in light of the experience gained in Afghanistan. Topics include the future place of NATO in defence and security policy; emerging regions of concern and interest; and nuclear weapons and arms control, including missile defence and the military use of space.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSecurity, International. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aBland, Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharron, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDewitt, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFergusson, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFergusson, James, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFurtado, Francis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFurtado, Francis, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHaglund, David G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJockel, Joseph T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlep